<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - world]]></title><link/> https://www.wsj.com/news/world <atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/wsj/en-us/world" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - world - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 8 月 12 日星期六 05:36:00 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[This 60-Year-Old Soviet Rocket Launcher Fights On in Ukraine]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Grad 的使用表明该国对老式武器的依赖，并伴随着风险<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834038/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="顿涅茨克地区，乌克兰第 60 旅的成员聚集在苏联制造的“格拉德”火箭发射器周围。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>顿涅茨克地区，乌克兰第 60 旅的成员聚集在苏联制造的“格拉德”火箭发射器周围。 <span></span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001127859"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001127859"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/alistair-macdonald" itemprop="url" rel="author">阿利斯泰尔·麦克唐纳</a></span>Serhii Korovayny 为《华尔街日报》拍摄的照片</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 12 日上午 12:00（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/this-60-year-old-soviet-rocket-launcher-fights-on-in-ukraine-c81690a9"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>乌克兰德鲁日基夫卡——西方政府已向乌克兰运送了一些世界上最先进的武器，但炮台指挥官弗拉基米尔·苏希洛夫使用的是已有 60 年历史的苏联火箭发射器，该发射器已成为这场战争中双方的主要武器。</p><p>尽管价值数十亿美元的导弹、榴弹炮和其他武器被运往乌克兰，但分析人士估计，该国至少三分之二的军械库是苏联遗产。老式武器在支持乌克兰军队<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-uses-small-unit-tactics-to-retake-captured-territory-from-russia-d9ef32a3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">缓慢的反攻</a>方面发挥着关键作用，因为军事指挥官扣留了一些受过西方训练的部队并捐赠了坦克等武器。</p><p>很少有武器比 BM-21 Grad 更能体现这种依赖，它是苏联武器的标志，于 1963 年开始服役，可从卡车后部发射多达 40 枚非制导火箭弹。</p><p>格雷德还显示了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/band-of-barbers-judges-and-security-guards-uses-soviet-era-guns-to-repel-russian-drones-11675485324?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">乌克兰依赖苏联时代装备</a>的危险。分析人士和一些运营商表示，这种老化的武器精度不高，容易出现故障，而该国的“冰雹”火箭供应量也已所剩无几。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834031?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">第 60 旅的连长弗拉基米尔·苏希洛夫 (Volodymyr Sukhilov) 称格雷德为“一位老太太”。 </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834029?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">苏希洛夫展示了他用来查找目标坐标的平板电脑软件。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>格拉德在乌克兰的军火库中广泛存在。美国向乌克兰派遣了38枚“希玛”现代移动火箭发射器， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/himars-transform-battle-for-ukraine-modern-warfare-11665169716?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">在战场上产生了巨大影响</a>。但根据国防情报组织 Janes 的说法，该国在发动战争时约有 260 名毕业生，而俄罗斯则有大约 500 名现役毕业生，还有更多的人在储存。</p><p>虽然毕业生的年龄带来了限制，但操作它的人仍然对他们称之为祖母和其他绰号的武器保持着感情。他们表示，它仍然可以有效地饱和俄罗斯的阵地。</p><p> “这是一位老太太，有着所有（老人的）问题，”乌克兰第 60 旅的苏希洛夫说。</p><p>该旅的六名毕业生中的一名大约 60 岁，他隐藏在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-struggles-to-retake-bakhmut-from-dogged-russian-fighters-c8945b93?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">战略城市巴赫穆特</a>附近前线村庄外的土堤和树木中。该武器经常出现机械问题，而其工作人员主要学会了修复这些问题。</p><p>苏希洛夫说：“最好问一下什么没有损坏。”</p><p>尽管如此，“Grad”（俄语中的意思是“冰雹”）仍然发挥着重要作用。</p><p>苏希洛夫说：“我们可以在短时间内向敌人发射大量火箭。” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/11c3acb2-5214-4d56-a139-77058b777e70.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>第 60 旅的 Grad 操作员表示，他们几乎没有看到西方装备，因此很想拥有一辆 Himars。</p><p> Himar 和其他现代多管火箭发射器可以通过卫星导航系统将火力引导至目标，而 Grad 操作员则手动输入坐标并自行定位武器。</p><p>炮兵们表示，“格拉德”火箭炮的用途与现代火箭发射器不同。他们说，虽然新型武器可以进行精确打击，但“格拉德”导弹可以打击整个战场。</p><p> Janes 分析师苏尼尔·奈尔 (Sunil Nair) 在描述束缚敌人并为己方部队提供掩护的做法时表示：“它不是最准确的，自动化程度也不是最高的，但它对于压制火力非常有效。”</p><p> “想象 20 秒内有 40 枚火箭弹落入目标区域，”他说。</p><p>人权观察称，这种不分青红皂白的轰炸对平民来说尤其危险。该非营利组织表示，“毕业生”齐射可以击中近 10 个足球场大小的区域。</p><p> Grad 的射程可达 25 英里，仅比 Himars 的四分之一多一点。</p><p>与现代移动火箭发射器不同，Grad 无法为坐在驾驶室中的操作员提供保护，驾驶室的金属和窗户并不比当时的普通卡车厚。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834032?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">第 60 旅有 6 名毕业生可供调遣。 </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834035?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">迷彩网掩盖了该旅的一名毕业生。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “如果毕业生<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-pivotal-mission-in-ukraines-counteroffensive-hunting-for-mines-78197558?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">击中反坦克地雷</a>，每个人都会死，”第 57 旅独立毕业生组的一名操作员说道。</p><p>尽管如此，操作员表示，在没有装甲重量的情况下，较轻的“格拉德”在潮湿的地面上的机动性比许多现代发射器更好。他们补充说，苏联车辆在没有火箭的情况下最高时速约为 50 英里，满载时最高时速可达 40 英里。</p><p>对于巴赫穆特附近的第 60 旅来说，Grad 最近被用来瞄准俄罗斯炮兵连和步兵。</p><p>在一个典型的日子里，旅指挥部通过无线电向炮台指挥官苏希洛夫提供目标并告诉他需要的火箭弹数量。苏希洛夫通过装有专门软件的平板电脑找到目标坐标，并向毕业生人员发送无线电指令。</p><p>一旦就位，武器操作员就可以在固定在车辆仪表板上的金属盒内的老式黄铜表盘上选择火箭的数量。然后炮兵打开车窗，将开关向右转动并按下红色按钮开火。</p><p>毕业生在前苏联国家及其盟国的军队中仍然无处不在。据简斯称，大约 50 个国家的武库中拥有这种武器或其变体。</p><p>分析人士称，自越南战争以来，“格拉德”几乎出现在所有武装冲突中，而该系统的火箭有时也由自制发射器发射。</p><p>乌克兰军事情报官员安德烈·切尔尼亚克表示，鉴于乌克兰自 2014 年以来一直与俄罗斯交战，所有苏联武器的弹药库存最终将耗尽。</p><p>苏联口径的子弹、火箭和炮弹的最大来源之一是俄罗斯，但这不是一个选择。切尔尼亚克表示，乌克兰正试图从其他地方补充库存。这是一个很大的问题。战略与国际研究中心国际安全项目顾问马克·坎西安表示，乌克兰大约三分之二的火炮仍然是苏联老式炮兵。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834034?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">尽管格雷德有缺点，但操作员经常充满感情地谈论这种武器。 </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834036?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">顿涅茨克的土地上有战壕，该地区曾经历过一些最激烈的战争。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>第60旅的炮兵表示，虽然他们仍然收到火箭弹补给，但他们正在更有选择性地选择目标。他们的车辆满载。</p><p>与此同时，第 57 旅的 Grad 操作员表示，他们已经两周没有开枪了。它的管道是空的。</p><p>第 57 旅的毕业典礼建于 20 世纪 70 年代，管道上的绿色油漆剥落。工作人员给这把武器起了个昵称“巴赫马托夫”，这是一位现已调职的前同事的姓氏。</p><p> “他像爱自己的妻子一样爱那个毕业生，”一名接线员说道。他说，这位前同事仍然打电话询问火箭发射器进展如何。</p><p>操作员们交换了他们第一次发射武器时的故事，他们说这是一次难忘的经历。这种声音损害了一些人的听力。</p><p>中士。来自第 60 旅的德米特罗·西蒙年科 (Dmytro Symonenko) 少校自 2014 年俄罗斯吞并克里米亚并在乌克兰东部煽动分裂主义运动以来一直在操作 Grads。</p><p>起初他会认为他的目标是人。现在他根本不去想他们了。</p><p> “俄罗斯人不应该在这里，他们需要离开，”西蒙年科说。</p><p>西蒙年科说，当“格拉德”号发射满载火箭时，就好像身处一条龙的体内。</p><p> “我永远不会厌倦，”他说。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834037?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">乌克兰炮兵部队一直在夺回俄罗斯占领的土地（包括该国东部）的战斗中寻求优势。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p class="articleTagLine"> — <em><em>Oksana</em> Pyrozhok</em>对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给阿利斯泰尔·麦克唐纳 (Alistair MacDonald)： <a href="mailto:Alistair.Macdonald@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Alistair.Macdonald@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 12 Aug 2023 04:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/this-60-year-old-soviet-rocket-launcher-fights-on-in-ukraine-c81690a9</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/this-60-year-old-soviet-rocket-launcher-fights-on-in-ukraine-c81690a9<author><![CDATA[Alistair MacDonald]]></author><category>乌克兰</category><category>航空航天/国防</category><category>工业品</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>武装部队</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>武器计划</category><category>乌克兰</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>武装部队</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>武器计划</category><category>航天</category><category>防御</category><category>工业品</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[China’s Home Buyers Are Waiting Out the Property Slump]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>潜在购房者预计价格会下跌，从而抑制新房销售并使振兴经济的政策努力变得复杂化<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001128238"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="507" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834708?width=860&amp;height=507" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">房地产市场的进一步下滑使政策制定者重振经济增长的努力变得更加复杂。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Cfoto/DDP/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001128238"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/cao-li" itemprop="url" rel="author">曹莉</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 12 日上午 12:00（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-home-buyers-are-waiting-out-the-property-slump-bcbf9239"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>在今年早些时候短暂的销售反弹之后，中国房地产市场再次陷入深度低迷， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/country-garden-chinas-largest-surviving-developer-sinks-into-debt-crisis-2a525173?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">开发商面临更多现金流问题</a>，中国当局正在尝试更多方法来重振住房需求。</p><p>潜在的购房者预计价格会下跌，并认为如果他们静观其变，就会出现更好的交易。</p><p>中国的房地产经纪人和经济学家表示，房屋销售再次下降，因为中国公民开始期望地方政府提供更多购房补贴、开发商降价以及银行提供更便宜的抵押贷款。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="900" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834012?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>这使得情况变得更糟，因为房地产开发商迫切需要出售更多房屋以赚取现金并避免债务违约。中国最大的幸存开发商<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/HK/XHKG/6098" class="">碧桂园</a>上周表示<span class="company-name-type">，</span>在其<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinese-property-giant-country-garden-sends-another-distress-signal-22b3bd64?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">公寓销售连续四个月下降</a>后，该公司遇到了流动性问题。该公司的财务困境给房地产市场带来了新的震动，这可能会进一步推迟其复苏。</p><p> “这并不是说他们不想买房。他们有购买需求，但只是在等待。”中国一家国有开发商的销售经理严松声在谈到他的客户时说道。</p><p>房地产市场的进一步下滑使北京政策制定者重振经济增长的努力变得更加复杂。中国已经在与青年失业率高、出口下降和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-slips-into-deflation-in-warning-sign-for-world-economy-bbefb179?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">通货紧缩环境作斗争。</a>信用评级公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MCO" class="company-name">穆迪投资者服务</a>公司周五在一份报告中表示，“购房者对该行业日益厌恶的情绪也可能削弱政府为稳定房地产销售而采取的任何潜在支持措施的效果。”</p><p>两年来，中国的房地产市场一直处于螺旋式下降的状态。根据私营行业追踪机构中国房地产信息的数据，上个月，中国 100 家最大的房地产开发商销售了价值 490 亿美元的新房，这是三年来的最低月度销售额。与六月份和去年同期相比，销售额下降了三分之一。也比 2021 年 7 月的总数减少了 59%。</p><p> 7 月往往是中国新房销售较慢的月份，因为开发商经常试图提高 6 月的销售量，以报告更好的上半年业绩。 6月，东部城市杭州的一家开发商提出，如果人们购买建筑面积超过1000平方英尺的房屋，就会赠送2.2磅黄金——价值约7万美元。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="900" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834013?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>最近的下跌幅度仍然令人惊讶。碧桂园7月份合同销售同比下降60%，降幅远超前几个月。</p><p>居住在中国南部广东省珠海市的颜先生表示，尽管他的公司为其销售的房产提供了更大的折扣，但他的团队 7 月份的销售额还不到上半年月平均销售额的四分之一。</p><p>经济学家表示，购房者的观望态度令人担忧，因为这可能会延长房地产市场以及中国经济的复苏。中国也<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-slips-into-deflation-in-warning-sign-for-world-economy-bbefb179?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">陷入了通货紧缩</a>，如果消费价格下降使人们期望为一系列商品支付更少的费用，这可能会造成损害。</p><p>为了吸引购房者，房地产开发商一直在提供免费停车和家用电器等福利。房地产经纪人表示，这让人们对此类免费赠品产生了期待，一旦优惠结束，销量就会下降。</p><p>中国商业银行还大幅下调了住房贷款利率，目前平均抵押贷款利率低于中国五年期贷款优惠利率（长期债务通常挂钩的基准）。近两年国家基准也多次下调。</p><p>过去几个月，中国 70 个主要城市的新建和转售房屋平均价格有所下降，政策制定者更加明确地表达了支持房地产市场的必要性。</p><p>去年年底，中国当局取消了导致数十家房地产开发商债务违约的去杠杆化行动，并推出了刺激需求的措施，并为幸存的开发商提供充足的融资。</p><p>再加上中国在新冠疫情后重新开放以及被压抑的购买需求，导致 2023 年前几个月房屋销售回升，这对开发商以及股票和债券投资者来说是一个可喜的缓解。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="860" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832315?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> 4月份房地产市场再次开始疲软。<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/SCGLY" class="">法国兴业银行</a>中国经济学家魏尧表示，随着房价下跌，更多人开始意识到房地产市场仍然存在大问题<span class="company-name-type">。</span></p><p> “加上整体经济复苏乏力，人们对收入和就业的预期和前景降低，人们变得更加现实，所有这些担忧可能会在7月份爆发，”她说。</p><p> 7月下旬，中国最高决策机构政治局表示，是时候调整房地产政策了，并多年来首次省略了长期以来的口头禅“房子是用来住的，不是用来炒的”。全国各城市采取了应对措施，包括现金补贴和购房退税、提高购房者从银行贷款的限额，以及取消额外购房的限制。</p><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MS" class="">摩根士丹利</a>首席中国经济学家 Robin Xing 表示，中国的年度住房需求预计在 9 至 1000 万套之间<span class="company-name-type">，</span>而 2021 年的峰值为 1400 万套，这一水平包括投机性购买。邢说，今年的销售速度低于预期的正常需求。</p><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/JLL" class="">仲量联行</a>首席中国经济学家 Bruce Pang 表示，在房地产市场出现好转之前，购房者几乎没有动力采取行动<span class="company-name-type">。</span> “跌得越多，人们就越失去信心。信心丧失得越多，人们购买的可能性就越小，”他说。</p><p>安徽省合肥市 24 岁的房地产经纪人王涛表示，他的许多客户都在等待显示市场走向的指标。 “他们告诉我，现在的价格不稳定，不知道会涨还是会跌。因此，他们宁愿保持静止来应对不断变化的环境，”他说。</p><p>写信给曹莉： <a href="mailto:li.cao@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">li.cao@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 12 Aug 2023 04:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-home-buyers-are-waiting-out-the-property-slump-bcbf9239</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-home-buyers-are-waiting-out-the-property-slump-bcbf9239<author><![CDATA[Cao Li]]></author><category>华尔街日报亚洲财经</category><category>建筑施工</category><category>住宅建筑施工</category><category>建造</category><category>房地产/建筑</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>销售数据</category><category>政府援助/赠款</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>经济表现/指标</category><category>房屋销售/住房负担能力数据</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>房屋销售数据</category><category>房价数据</category><category>房地产市场</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>个人财务</category><category>房地产/物业</category><category>购买/出售房屋</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>房屋买卖</category><category>碧桂园服务控股</category><category>6098.HK</category><category>港币:6098</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>销售数据</category><category>政府援助</category><category>赠款</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>经济表现</category><category>指标</category><category>房屋销售</category><category>住房负担能力数据</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>房屋销售数据</category><category>房价数据</category><category>房地产市场</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>个人财务</category><category>房地产</category><category>财产</category><category>购买</category><category>卖房子</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>房屋买卖</category><category>建筑施工</category><category>住宅建筑施工</category><category>建造</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Ecuador Assassination Reflects Rapid Rise of Violent Cocaine Trade]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>卡特尔和帮派已经将这个曾经基本和平的安第斯国家变成了费尔南多·比亚维森西奥曾承诺要解决的贩毒中心<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834391/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="厄瓜多尔总统候选人费尔南多·维拉维森西奥周三在基多举行的竞选集会上，几分钟后被枪杀。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>厄瓜多尔总统候选人费尔南多·维拉维森西奥周三在基多举行的竞选集会上，几分钟后被枪杀。 API/美联社<span>API/美联社</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001130067"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001130067"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ryan-dube" itemprop="url" rel="author">瑞安·杜贝 (Ryan Dubé)</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jose-decordoba" itemprop="url" rel="author">何塞·德科尔多瓦 (José de Córdoba)</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 11 日晚上 8:19 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ecuador-assassination-reflects-rapid-rise-of-violent-cocaine-trade-aa27aedc"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>在被枪杀的四天前，总统候选人费尔南多·比亚维森西奥前往厄瓜多尔太平洋海岸附近一个尘土飞扬的小镇，在自己的地盘上反抗该国最残酷的贩毒团伙之一。</p><p> “来吧，我来了，”他在闷热的乔内镇举行的竞选集会上说道，这里是乔内罗斯团伙的发源地，该团伙一直处于该国<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/cocaine-trade-and-gang-violence-strike-hard-in-once-peaceful-ecuador-bad953c8?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">毒品屠杀</a>的中心。 “他们让我穿防弹背心，但我在这里只穿着一件汗湿的衬衫。”</p><p> 59 岁的比亚维森西奥在担任记者和后来的政治家的职业生涯中，经常与统治这个 1800 万人口国家的有权势的人发生冲突。</p><p>同事们说，他通过对政府腐败的调查而树敌，迫使他一度躲藏在亚马逊地区。在8月20日大选前的竞选活动中，他承诺打击有组织犯罪和贩毒团伙，他称这些团伙腐蚀了警察、法官和政治权力高层，厄瓜多尔政治分析人士也认同这一说法。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ecuador-presidential-candidate-who-had-denounced-gangs-is-assassinated-dad61aa5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">周三，他在首都基多被明目张胆地杀害</a>——这是厄瓜多尔首次出现总统候选人被暗杀的事件——让人们关注到蓬勃发展的可卡因贸易和助长残暴暴力的大胆帮派的腐蚀性影响。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834397?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">距离厄瓜多尔总统选举不到两周，人们在费尔南多·比亚维森西奥的集会上躲避枪击。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>基多咨询公司 Profitas 总裁塞巴斯蒂安·乌尔塔多 (Sebastian Hurtado) 表示：“比亚维森西奥被杀标志着一个前因后果。” “这不仅仅是一场杀戮，也是一场政治行动，将产生立竿见影的影响。”</p><p>这次暗杀事件发生时，厄瓜多尔已经陷入混乱，非常不受欢迎的总统吉列尔莫·拉索在五月<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ecuador-president-dissolves-congress-ahead-of-impeachment-vote-987f5883?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">解散国民议会</a>后通过法令执政。数万人<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/andes-turmoil-rattles-governments-spurs-migration-to-u-s-d8396753?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">向北逃往美国</a>，多年来在一个相对和平的国家运作的国家安全部门面临着来自资金充足且暴力的贩毒团伙的前所未有的挑战。</p><p>基多的安全专家丹尼尔·庞顿（Daniel Pontón）表示，混乱的局势是贩毒团伙滋生的沃土。</p><p> “一个混乱的国家总是更有利于犯罪，”他说。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834640?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">费尔南多·比亚维森西奥去世后，总统吉列尔莫·拉索宣布厄瓜多尔进入紧急状态。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：胡安·迭戈·黑山/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>周四，内政部官员表示， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ecuador-declares-state-of-emergency-after-presidential-candidate-killed-6e639e72?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">六名哥伦比亚嫌疑人因杀害比亚维森西奥而被捕</a>，比亚维森西奥在离开基多的一场竞选活动时头部中弹。一名高级警官表示，这些人与一个吸食可卡因的有组织犯罪集团有联系，但具体动机尚未确定。</p><p>厄瓜多尔是一个面积与俄勒冈州相当的国家，夹在哥伦比亚和秘鲁之间（这两个国家种植的可卡因叶子主要用于制造可卡因），厄瓜多尔与可卡因相关的犯罪问题一直处于边缘地位。</p><p>随后发生了两项重大事态发展：哥伦比亚结束了美国支持的古柯（用于制造可卡因的叶子）的空中熏蒸，以及厄瓜多尔贩毒集团主要领导人死亡后暴力事件激增。</p><p> 2015 年厄瓜多尔北部邻国空中喷药结束导致<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/colombias-acreage-of-coca-used-to-make-cocaine-surges-to-record-11666306614?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">作物和成品大幅增加</a>。随着更多的可卡因运往厄瓜多尔（出口到欧洲和美国之前的最后一站），贩毒团伙开始争夺不断增长的业务。</p><p> “每个人都想控制航线和港口，”厄瓜多尔军队前情报总监马里奥·帕兹米诺说。 “这就是我们发生这些对抗的原因。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834393?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">厄瓜多尔警方公布的一张照片显示，因涉嫌杀害费尔南多·比亚维森西奥而被捕的嫌疑人。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：厄瓜多尔警察/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834398?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">警方展示在暗杀事件后缴获的枪支。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：厄瓜多尔警方/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>当地安全专家表示，对于毒贩来说，通过厄瓜多尔运送毒品更容易、更便宜，因为厄瓜多尔的边境漏洞百出，道路良好，太平洋大型港口安全保障薄弱。</p><p>厄瓜多尔与美国缉毒机构的合作减少——这是 2009 年决定停止美国从太平洋沿岸曼塔空军基地起飞的缉毒航班的副产品——也使得厄瓜多尔比哥伦比亚对运输可卡因更具吸引力。执法管理局长期以来与警方密切合作。</p><p>厄瓜多尔当局近年来缉获的可卡因凸显了该国对全球毒品走私的重要性。联合国毒品和犯罪问题办公室 (UNODC) 最近报告称，来自厄瓜多尔运往欧洲的可卡因比例从 2019 年的 9% 上升到 2021 年的 33%。联合国和禁毒官员表示，可卡因还大量从厄瓜多尔北部流向中美洲，然后流向墨西哥和美国。</p><p>荷兰当局周四报告称，他们 7 月份在鹿特丹港缉获了约 8 吨可卡因，价值约 6.6 亿美元，这是该港口有史以来缉获的最大可卡因。可卡因与香蕉一起藏在一艘从厄瓜多尔出发的船上的集装箱中。</p><p>一名西方官员表示，大量可卡因流经厄瓜多尔，当局在如何销毁缴获的毒品方面陷入困境。另一位毒品专家、维也纳毒品和犯罪问题办公室的安托万·维拉（Antoine Vella）详细撰写了有关可卡因的文章，他说：“这是一个蓬勃发展的市场。厄瓜多尔正在付出代价。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834649?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">荷兰当局表示，他们上个月从一艘从厄瓜多尔出发的船上查获了价值 6.6 亿美元的可卡因。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：荷兰海关/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>据政府官员和安全专家称，爆炸性增长导致了新帮派的到来，其中包括利用宽松的签证要求的阿尔巴尼亚黑手党。</p><p>墨西哥两大贩毒组织锡那罗亚贩毒集团和哈利斯科新一代贩毒集团与厄瓜多尔犯罪团伙结盟。常驻华盛顿的国际安全顾问道格拉斯·法拉赫 (Douglas Farah) 经常撰写有关该地区毒品贸易的文章，他表示，哈利斯科卡特尔在墨西哥通过杀害政客和法官来挑战国家政权，现已成为厄瓜多尔的主要墨西哥组织。</p><p>美国海军学院拉丁美洲问题专家约翰·波尔加-赫西莫维奇表示，2020 年 12 月，厄瓜多尔最强大的贩毒集团乔内罗斯 (Choneros) 头目豪尔赫·路易斯·赞布拉诺 (Jorge Luis Zambrano) 被暗杀，这是引发厄瓜多尔暴力升级的关键因素。</p><p> “它摧毁了乔内罗斯对贩毒的垄断，造成了权力真空，并引发了激烈的业务竞争，”波尔加-赫西莫维奇说。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834410?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">总统候选人费尔南多·比亚维森西奥的支持者在他被杀后走上街头。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：圣地亚哥·费尔南德斯/EPA/Shutterstock</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>据内政部称，凶杀案自 2019 年以来增加了四倍，去年达到创纪录的 4,800 起，使这个深受美国退休人员欢迎的国家成为拉丁美洲最危险的国家之一。由帮派控制的监狱里发生的可怕屠杀是家常便饭。枪手杀害警察和检察官。</p><p> “很明显，我们在打击这些贩毒集团的战争中正在失败，”总统候选人简·托皮克(Jan Topic)说，他呼吁像<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-country-with-the-highest-murder-rate-now-has-the-highest-incarceration-rate-b5401da7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">萨尔瓦多</a>总统纳伊布·布克莱(Nayib Bukele)那样对帮派进行镇压。 “我们现在最大的问题是缺乏战略、缺乏计划、缺乏目标。”</p><p>在竞选期间，比亚维森西奥是最强烈支持追捕毒贩的人之一。他承诺在亚马逊地区为帮派头目建造一座安全级别最高的监狱，扩大与美国的禁毒合作，并清除警察中的腐败官员。</p><p>比亚维森西奥的妻子维罗尼卡·萨拉乌斯 (Verónica Sarauz) 表示，她的丈夫之所以成为目标，是因为他愿意追捕有组织犯罪。比亚维森西奥曾谈到来自 Choneros 的威胁，这是一个 20 世纪 90 年代出现的由监狱领导的组织，据信与墨西哥锡那罗亚贩毒集团合作。</p><p> “他们杀了我的丈夫，因为他是这个国家唯一对抗政治黑手党和毒贩的人，”她在 X（该网站以前称为 Twitter）上写道。<br>安全专家表示，厄瓜多尔法治的崩溃引发了人们对拉丁美洲其他地区有组织犯罪加剧的担忧。贩毒团伙在哥伦比亚和委内瑞拉的一些地区以及中美洲和墨西哥北部不断扩张。</p><p>华盛顿安全顾问法拉赫表示，“随着犯罪集团取代国家，整个西半球的民主都受到攻击。” “这是法治消失的预兆之一。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834402?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">周四，一辆灵车载着费尔南多·比亚维森西奥的尸体离开基多的太平间。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：卡洛斯·诺列加/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p class="articleTagLine">——胡安·福雷罗对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Ryan Dubé（ <a href="mailto:ryan.dube@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">ryan.dube@wsj.com）</a>和 José de Córdoba（ <a href="mailto:jose.decordoba@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jose.decordoba@wsj.com</a> ）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 12 Aug 2023 00:19:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ecuador-assassination-reflects-rapid-rise-of-violent-cocaine-trade-aa27aedc</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ecuador-assassination-reflects-rapid-rise-of-violent-cocaine-trade-aa27aedc<author><![CDATA[Ryan DubéJosé de Córdoba]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>毒品贩运/交易</category><category>帮派</category><category>凶杀案</category><category>犯罪企业</category><category>贩运/走私</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>费尔南多·比亚维森西奥</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>贩毒</category><category>交易</category><category>帮派</category><category>凶杀案</category><category>犯罪企业</category><category>贩卖</category><category>走私</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Judge Sends FTX’s Sam Bankman-Fried to Jail]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>曾经的加密货币企业家在美国法警给他戴上手铐之前将个人物品交给了他的律师<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001129268"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=8B408483-348D-445E-AB7A-2A7C13A60F2E&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fjudge-sends-ftxs-sam-bankman-fried-to-jail-ahead-of-fraud-trial-79740119&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">倒闭的加密货币交易所 FTX 的创始人 Sam Bankman-Fried 因涉嫌在等待欺诈指控审判期间试图影响和篡改证人而被判入狱。照片：爱德华多·穆尼奥斯/路透社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001129268"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/james-fanelli" itemprop="url" rel="author">詹姆斯·法内利</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/corinne-ramey" itemprop="url" rel="author">科琳·雷米</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 11 日下午 5:02（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/judge-sends-ftxs-sam-bankman-fried-to-jail-ahead-of-fraud-trial-79740119"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>周五，一名联邦法官撤销了 FTX 创始人 Sam Bankman-Fried 的保释并将<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sam-bankman-fried-faces-new-scrutiny-for-pretrial-conduct-d181e524?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">他送进监狱</a>。</p><p>这一决定结束了司法部与这位曾经的加密货币企业家之间长达数月的争论，原因是他在等待欺诈指控审判期间的行为。</p><p>美国地区法官刘易斯·卡普兰在纽约举行的听证会上表示，班克曼-弗里德一再<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sam-bankman-fried-accused-of-trying-to-discredit-witness-in-ftx-fraud-case-715b243a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">突破保释条件的限制</a>，可能犯有联邦罪行。</p><p>卡普兰说：“有可能有理由相信被告至少两次试图篡改证人。”</p><p>班克曼-弗里德的一名律师表示，他打算对该命令提出上诉。</p><p>法官结束听证会后，班克曼-弗里德将他的西装外套、领带和鞋带交给了律师，然后被美国法警戴上手铐。听证会结束时， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sam-bankman-frieds-parents-were-there-for-ftxs-rise-and-now-its-fall-11670841001?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">班克曼-弗里德的母亲</a>有时会抱着头哭泣。她试图在法庭上接近她的儿子，但法警阻止了她。</p><p>自从曼哈顿美国检察官办公室指控班克曼-弗里德从其<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/crypto-crisis-a-timeline-of-key-events-11675519887?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">加密货币交易所</a>的客户那里<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ftxs-sam-bankman-fried-charged-with-criminal-fraud-conspiracy-11670951131?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">窃取数十亿美元</a>，同时欺骗贷方和投资者以来，班克曼-弗里德一直被软禁在父母位于加州的房子里。他的审判定于 10 月 2 日开始，审判涉及与<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sam-bankman-fried-ftx-alameda-bankruptcy-collapse-11668824201?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">加密货币交易所倒闭</a>有关的七项刑事罪名。</p><p>班克曼-弗里德对这些指控表示不认罪。他承认犯了错误，但表示他没有欺骗任何人。</p><p>在审判之前，尚无法确定班克曼-弗里德将被拘留在哪里。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834484?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">倒闭的加密货币交易所 FTX 的创始人 Sam Bankman-Fried 于周五抵达曼哈顿联邦法院参加保释听证会。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：迈克尔·M·圣地亚哥/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>纽约联邦检察官要求法官监禁班克曼-弗里德，因为他们称班克曼-弗里德试图篡改证人并向一名到访他家的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NYT" class="company-name">《纽约时报》</a>记者提供了卡罗琳·埃里森的私人著作，</p>他的前女友和加密货币交易公司 Alameda Research 的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-caroline-ellison-found-herself-at-the-center-of-the-ftx-crypto-collapse-11668899604?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">前首席执行官</a>。 《泰晤士报》在埃里森的简介中使用了这些著作，预计埃里森将在审判中作证指控班克曼-弗里德。<p></p><p>检察官在本月早些时候的一封信中写道：“面对一系列旨在限制被告使用互联网和电话的条件，被告转向亲自策划。”</p><p>班克曼-弗里德的律师承认，他曾与记者交谈并为《纽约时报》的报道提供信息，但他们表示，他这样做是为了保护自己的声誉。他们说，他的案件引起了媒体的广泛关注，他们的当事人正在行使第一修正案的权利，以打击对自己的负面描述。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>卡普兰表示，他很重视班克曼-弗里德的第一修正案权利，并且频繁与媒体接触并不构成妨碍或篡改证人。</p><p>但法官表示，班克曼-弗里德与证人的接触以及他对埃里森私人著作的分享使他得出结论，被告的意图是，“即使是适度的，也是为了影响那些人，让他们退缩，让他们对冲”他们与政府的合作。”</p><p>法官表示，《泰晤士报》记者在班克曼-弗里德的家中查看了这些文件，但没有收到他的副本。</p><p>卡普兰说：“在他看来，这是一种最不可能被捕的方式。” “他正在掩盖自己的踪迹。”</p><p>班克曼-弗里德的律师表示，监禁他将妨碍他<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/judge-weighs-whether-sam-bankman-fried-will-face-two-criminal-trials-b06e0ad0?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">准备审判的</a>能力，侵犯了他的第六修正案权利。他们说，这位<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/at-ftx-multimillion-dollar-expenses-were-approved-by-emoji-fb91bb3a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">曾经的加密货币企业家</a>整天都在审查相关文件，同时通过电话、电子邮件和 Zoom 与他的法律团队分享他的分析。他们说，监狱将极大地限制对记录和互联网的访问。</p><p>检察官建议班克曼-弗里德可能被拘留在纽约普特南县惩教所，并表示监狱将能够为他提供笔记本电脑和互联网接入，以帮助他为辩护做好准备。</p><p>卡普兰提出了将他关押在布鲁克林大都会拘留中心的可能性，纽约市的联邦囚犯通常被关押在那里。</p><p>他补充说，他会考虑做出安排，例如花时间在律师办公室，让班克曼-弗里德继续准备辩护，但他相信拘留不会妨碍公平审判。</p><p> “我不认为撤销保释是一个已经提出的难以克服的问题，”卡普兰说。</p><p>写信给 James Fanelli <a href="mailto:james.fanelli@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">(james.fanelli@wsj.com)</a>和 Corinne Ramey ( <a href="mailto:corinne.ramey@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">corinne.ramey@wsj.com</a> )</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          inline
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>FTX创始人在候审期间是否应该入狱？为什么或者为什么不？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 21:02:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/judge-sends-ftxs-sam-bankman-fried-to-jail-ahead-of-fraud-trial-79740119</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/judge-sends-ftxs-sam-bankman-fried-to-jail-ahead-of-fraud-trial-79740119<author><![CDATA[James FanelliCorinne Ramey]]></author><category>华尔街日报财经</category><category>华尔街日报-美国新闻</category><category>金融投资服务</category><category>证券/商品交易活动</category><category>银行/信贷</category><category>加密货币交易所</category><category>金融服务</category><category>金融科技</category><category>投资/证券</category><category>技术</category><category>虚拟货币/加密货币</category><category>企业犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>欺诈罪</category><category>证人篡改</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>萨姆·班克曼-弗里德</category><category>企业犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>欺诈罪</category><category>证人篡改</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>金融投资服务</category><category>证券</category><category>商品交换活动</category><category>银行业</category><category>信用</category><category>加密货币交易所</category><category>金融服务</category><category>金融科技</category><category>投资</category><category>技术</category><category>虚拟货币</category><category>加密货币</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Hunter Biden Plea Talks Break Down as DOJ Names Special Counsel]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>司法部长梅里克·加兰（Merrick Garland）授予美国检察官大卫·韦斯（David Weiss）更广泛的权力，以对总统的儿子提出指控<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001128628"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=8F100B27-8D38-40F9-9043-D86075174137&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fmerrick-garland-names-david-weiss-as-special-counsel-in-hunter-biden-investigation-a2ad0ba4&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">司法部长梅里克·加兰周五表示，他将把大卫·韦斯的身份改为亨特·拜登调查中的特别检察官。照片：斯蒂芬妮·斯卡布勒/美联社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001128628"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sadie-gurman" itemprop="url" rel="author">Sadie Gurman</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/aruna-viswanatha" itemprop="url" rel="author">Aruna Viswanatha</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 11 日下午 4:39（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/merrick-garland-names-david-weiss-as-special-counsel-in-hunter-biden-investigation-a2ad0ba4"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> WASHINGTON—Attorney General Merrick Garland on Friday named Delaware US Attorney David Weiss as a special counsel to continue his prosecution of Hunter Biden after plea talks broke down, opening a new, politically fraught chapter in <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hunter-biden-plea-deal-limbo-republicans-749b5187?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the long-running legal drama</a> as his father, President Biden, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/joe-and-hunter-biden-ignores-political-perils-and-embraces-scandal-plagued-son-f105aee2?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">campaigns for re-election</a> .</p><p> The appointment, which allows Weiss to prosecute Hunter Biden in any district he deems appropriate rather than solely in Delaware, came the same day Weiss said in a court filing that plea talks with Biden were at an impasse and prosecutors expected the case against him to go to trial.</p><p> Weiss asked a federal judge in Delaware to dismiss a previously filed tax case against Hunter Biden, saying prosecutors needed to try the case elsewhere, including in California, where Biden lived during the years at issue in the case.</p><p> Garland said Weiss had told him on Tuesday that his investigation had “reached a stage at which he should continue his work as a special counsel, and he asked to be so appointed.” Garland, who had previously insisted Weiss had all the necessary resources and autonomy, said the move “reaffirms that Mr. Weiss has the authority he needs to conduct a thorough investigation and continue to take the steps he deems appropriate independently, based only on the facts and the law.”</p><p> A lawyer for Hunter Biden, Chris Clark, said Biden&#39;s legal team still believed they could resolve the case without a trial. “We are confident when all of these maneuverings are at an end, my client will have resolution and will be moving on with his life successfully,” he said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834291?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Attorney General Merrick Garland on Friday noted &#39;extraordinary circumstances&#39; relating to the Hunter Biden investigation.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Drew Angerer/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Weiss&#39;s appointment puts the Justice Department in the middle of an unprecedented scenario in which three different special counsels are investigating the president, his son, and the president&#39;s likely chief rival for the 2024 campaign, GOP front-runner <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/donald-trump">Donald Trump</a> .</p><p> Special counsel Jack Smith <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-trial-special-counsel-jack-smith-prosecutors-team-20d57b78?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">has charged Trump</a> with improperly withholding classified documents and separately to conspiring to illegally overturn his 2020 election loss; Trump has pleaded not guilty in both cases. Another special counsel, Robert Hur, has been examining President Biden&#39;s <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/robert-hur-brings-experience-with-political-pressure-to-special-counsel-role-11673562204?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">handling of classified materials</a> , after such documents dating to before his time at the White House were found at his home and office.</p><p> Weiss had already been operating largely independently, telling lawmakers last month that he had “never been denied the authority to bring charges in any jurisdiction.”</p><p> The new status means Weiss isn&#39;t subject to day-to-day supervision by Justice Department leadership, though he must inform senior officials of significant decisions he seeks to make. He also will have to write and submit a report of his work that the attorney general can then make public. If the attorney general rejects any of his actions, Garland would have to explain that to Congress, under special-counsel regulations.</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> Congressional Republicans have been investigating business dealings involving Hunter Biden and the Biden family and decried the now jeopardized plea arrangement as overly lenient compared with the Justice Department&#39;s tough line on Trump. The criticism has been fueled in part by two investigators on the case alleging improper political interference.</p><p> “Let&#39;s be clear what today&#39;s move is really about,” said House Oversight Committee Chairman James Comer (R., Ky.), who has been <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/gop-lawmakers-two-jobs-investigating-bidens-managing-firebrands-a43c414?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">leading the congressional probe</a> . “The Biden Justice Department is trying to stonewall congressional oversight.”</p><p> Rep. Jim Jordan (R., Ohio), chair of the House Judiciary Committee, expressed skepticism about Garland&#39;s action despite having once called for a special counsel in the case. “First, David Weiss said he didn&#39;t have the power he needed and wanted special counsel status. Then, he said he had all the power he needs,” Jordan tweeted Friday. “Now, he gets special counsel status because he didn&#39;t really have the power he needs? Something&#39;s not right.”</p><p> Sen. Dick Durbin (D., Ill.), chair of the Senate Judiciary Committee, said the attorney general&#39;s move showed he wanted to avoid “even the appearance of politicization at the Justice Department,” adding that stance stood “in stark contrast to former President Trump&#39;s repeated efforts to use the Justice Department and Attorney General as his personal lawyer.”</p><p> Neither the White House nor Hunter Biden&#39;s lawyers were informed of the plan ahead of the announcement, a person familiar with the matter said. The White House didn&#39;t comment, referring questions to the Justice Department and Hunter Biden&#39;s legal team.</p><p> The appointment was the latest twist in a meandering and politically explosive investigation into Hunter Biden&#39;s finances, business dealings and well-documented drug and alcohol addiction.</p><p> The investigation has stretched on since 2018 under Weiss, who was appointed to the US attorney post by Trump and has remained in office under the Biden administration to see through the criminal inquiry. Garland has said <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/garland-defends-independence-of-hunter-biden-plea-deal-amid-gop-criticism-e8d8d0dd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">he gave Weiss free rein</a> to pursue the probe as he saw fit.</p><p> Hunter Biden <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hunter-biden-plea-deal-in-jeopardy-ff556d70?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">pleaded not guilty</a> last month to federal tax charges, a surprise reversal that came after US District Judge Maryellen Noreika refused to sign off on the earlier deal he had reached to plead guilty to tax charges and enter a separate agreement to resolve a gun charge. The judge said she needed more information and time to review the deal, citing what she described as the atypical provisions in it. On Friday, prosecutors said talks to salvage the gun agreement had also broken down. The judge asked Hunter Biden&#39;s team to respond to the government&#39;s filing by Monday.</p><p> In the plea hearing, prosecutors also disclosed that they were still investigating Biden and said he could face additional charges, including over potential violations of law that requires lobbyists for foreign governments or companies to register that work.</p><p> Two criminal agents from the Internal Revenue Service who worked on the investigation have alleged that political considerations appeared to infect investigative decisions at various stages in the probe, and that Biden appeared to receive preferential treatment not afforded other investigative targets.</p><p> The agents told lawmakers that prosecutors and Weiss had earlier recommended felony tax charges against Biden, even though Biden was ultimately offered a deal that involved only pleading guilty to two misdemeanor counts of willful failure to pay federal income tax, and Weiss&#39;s office had agreed to recommend a sentence of probation alone. A felony tax crime would likely entail some prison time, though any sentence is ultimately up to the judge overseeing the case.</p><p> In an op-ed last month, one of the IRS agents, Joseph Ziegler, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-special-counsel-for-hunter-biden-justice-irs-tax-whistleblower-2fe10db1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">urged Garland to appoint a special counsel</a> to independently review the matter. “What I saw during the investigation was entirely outside the norm,” Ziegler said.</p><p> Weiss told the House Judiciary Committee in a June letter: “I have indeed been granted ultimate authority over this matter, including responsibility for deciding when, where and whether to file charges and for making necessary decisions to preserve the integrity of the prosecution.”</p><p> In a subsequent letter, Weiss said he had never sought appointment as special counsel, and a person familiar with the matter confirmed that Tuesday was the first time he asked for that status.</p><p> Under the agreement Biden had reached with prosecutors, he admitted to making more than $1.5 million in annual income in both 2017 and 2018, much of which came from foreign sources. Biden also acknowledged that he worked with an accountant to prepare his tax returns but never actually filed them at the time or paid what he owed, in a period in which he was addicted to crack cocaine.</p><p> In 2021, a Biden associate paid $1.9 million to the IRS to cover those taxes, interest and penalties.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Annie Linskey contributed to this article.</p><p> Write to Sadie Gurman at <a href="mailto:sadie.gurman@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">sadie.gurman@wsj.com</a> and Aruna Viswanatha at <a href="mailto:aruna.viswanatha@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">aruna.viswanatha@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 20:39:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/merrick-garland-names-david-weiss-as-special-counsel-in-hunter-biden-investigation-a2ad0ba4</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/merrick-garland-names-david-weiss-as-special-counsel-in-hunter-biden-investigation-a2ad0ba4<author><![CDATA[Sadie GurmanAruna Viswanatha]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> David Weiss</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[U.N.-Led Team Completes Risky Operation to Transfer Oil From Decaying Tanker]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The FSO Safer had threatened to spill or explode and cause an environmental and humanitarian disaster in the Red Sea area <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001128913"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=93CC5459-0AE3-46E2-B205-5B3515994E17&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fu-n-led-team-completes-risky-operation-to-transfer-oil-from-decaying-yemen-tanker-150ec6d2&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> A team of international experts has completed a mission to transfer more than one million barrels of oil from an abandoned tanker off Yemen&#39;s Red Sea coast. WSJ&#39;s Sune Rasmussen explains what was at stake in this high-risk operation. Photo: Yahya Arhab/Zuma Press<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001128913"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sune-engel-rasmussen" itemprop="url" rel="author">Sune Engel Rasmussen</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated Aug. 11, 2023 3:22 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-n-led-team-completes-risky-operation-to-transfer-oil-from-decaying-yemen-tanker-150ec6d2"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> A team of international experts led by the United Nations finished a risky operation to siphon more than a million barrels of oil from <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-race-to-avert-an-oil-spill-that-could-cost-20-billion-to-fix-85a884ea?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a rusting tanker moored off Yemen&#39;s Red Sea coast</a> , where for years it threatened to explode or spill and cause an ecological and humanitarian disaster.</p><p> Two weeks after salvage workers launched the operation to transfer the oil from the 47-year-old FSO Safer, which had been left stranded 5 miles off the northern Yemeni shore since it was abandoned during the country&#39;s bloody, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/saudi-arabia-houthis-advance-toward-long-term-cease-fire-in-yemen-afa10c9b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">eight-year civil war</a> , the UN said Friday that the transfer was complete.</p><p> UN Secretary-General António Guterres said the transfer of the oil avoided “what could have been a monumental environmental and humanitarian catastrophe.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834289?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The FSO Safer tanker off the coast of Yemen in June before the oil transfer operation began.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Osamah Abdulrahman/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The tanker&#39;s corroding state has since 2019 alarmed international organizations and experts who feared a massive spill of oil into the region&#39;s fragile ecosystem that could cost $20 billion to clean up, according to the UN The oil, if disgorged, would have amounted to the fifth-largest oil spill from a tanker in history, disturbed one of the world&#39;s busiest shipping lanes and closed off ports bringing humanitarian aid into the war-torn country.</p><p> The operation had been delayed for years, as Yemen&#39;s Houthi rebels rebuffed requests from international organizations to access the tanker. With the mediation of a Yemen-based company, the Fahem Group, which imports grain through the nearby Hodeidah port, and which convinced the rebels that a spill would also damage their economic and political interests, a deal was struck last year to solve the issue.</p><p> The entire endeavor has taken more than two months. In late May, a 65-person crew from a Dutch salvage company, SMIT, arrived at the site to assess the condition of the vessel. They checked the rusty hull, replaced faulty parts and pumped inert gas into the tanks to lower the risk of explosion. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="402" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834293?width=700&amp;height=402" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The Nautica, a replacement oil tanker, gets tugged to parallel the decaying FSO Safer, off the coast of Yemen.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: SAFER TECHNICAL COMMITTEE/via REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> After the assessment, a very large crude carrier purchased by the UN lined up alongside the Safer, where the tanks of the two vessels were connected with pipes before the oil was transferred using hydraulic pumps. The transfer began on July 25 and was completed two weeks later, at 6 pm local time Friday.</p><p> The salvage vessel containing the oil will now be taken to a nearby location and secured to a specially strengthened buoy anchored to the seabed with thick cables within an estimated 10 days.</p><p> The FSO Safer will eventually be towed to a nearby port, the location of which hasn&#39;t been decided, where it will be cleaned of sludge, constituting approximately 2% of the total amount of oil, or the equivalent of roughly 22,000 barrels of oil.</p><p> While it brings immediate relief, the completion of the transfer also opens a new set of disputes. The FSO Safer and its contents belong to the Yemeni government, but both the toppled administration, now based in Aden, and the Houthis who occupy the capital San&#39;a claim to be Yemen&#39;s legitimate rulers.</p><p> No agreement has been made about the fate of the oil. If sold, the parties will have to agree on what happens to the profits. If it is to be stored in the new replacement vessel, money will have to be raised for the operation of the tanker.</p><p> The UN still lacks funding to complete the rest of the mission. The UN&#39;s plan is to clean the FSO Safer of sludge and scrap it at a green salvage yard, using the profits to bridge the gap in funding, Achim Steiner, administrator of the United Nations Development Programme told reporters Friday. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=93CC5459-0AE3-46E2-B205-5B3515994E17&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fu-n-led-team-completes-risky-operation-to-transfer-oil-from-decaying-yemen-tanker-150ec6d2&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> A team of international experts has launched an effort to transfer more than one million barrels of oil from an abandoned tanker before it spills off Yemen&#39;s Red Sea coast. WSJ&#39;s Sune Rasmussen explains what&#39;s at stake in this high-risk operation. Photo: Yahya Arhab/Zuma Press<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>Yet that won&#39;t be enough to make up for the shortfall in funding, Steiner said, calling on commercial actors to help out.</p><p> “Let me also say this very frankly here,” he said. “I think there are many in the industry that may still seize this moment to step forward where they have not stepped forward so far and help to close this financing gap.”</p><p> Write to Sune Engel Rasmussen at <a href="mailto:sune.rasmussen@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">sune.rasmussen@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 19:22:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/un-led-team-completes-risky-operation-to-transfer-oil-from-decaying-yemen-tanker-150ec6d2</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/un-led-team-completes-risky-operation-to-transfer-oil-from-decaying-yemen-tanker-150ec6d2<author><![CDATA[Sune Engel Rasmussen]]></author><category> Marine Transport</category><category>货运/物流</category><category>Marine Freight</category><category>水路运输/航运</category><category>Transportation/Logistics</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>发展/人道主义援助</category><category>国际关系</category><category>灾害/事故</category><category>Natural Environment</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>Environmental Pollution</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>development</category><category>人道主义援助</category><category>国际关系</category><category>灾难</category><category>事故</category><category>natural environment</category><category>政治</category><category>environmental pollution</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>marine transport</category><category>货运</category><category>logistics</category><category> marine freight</category><category>水运</category><category>shipping</category><category> transportation</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Iran Slows Buildup of Uranium Needed for Weapon]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Steps to ease tensions as Iran releases four US citizens from prison <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001128794"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="521" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834154?width=860&amp;height=521" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Centrifuge machines at the Natanz Uranium Enrichment Facility in Iran. Since the US left the 2015 Iranian nuclear accord, Tehran has massively expanded its program.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: /Associated Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001128794"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/laurence-norman" itemprop="url" rel="author">Laurence Norman</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 11, 2023 1:17 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/iran-slows-buildup-of-near-weapons-grade-enriched-uranium-492df473"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> LONDON—Iran has significantly slowed the pace at which it is accumulating near-weapons-grade enriched uranium and has diluted some of its stockpile, people briefed on the matter said Friday, moves that could help ease tensions with the US and allow the resumption of broader talks over <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/iran-could-produce-nuclear-weapon-in-several-months-if-it-decides-to-do-so-mark-milley-says-ecd38f07?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">its controversial nuclear program.</a></p><p> The more slowly Tehran accumulates highly enriched uranium, the less potential fissile material it has for nuclear weapons.</p><p> The news comes a day after <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/iran-releases-four-americans-from-evin-prison-b396ee09?mod=world_major_2_pos1&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Iran released four US citizens from prison into house arrest</a> , the first step in a planned prisoner swap that Washington expects will eventually see them return home. If the US detainees are set free, Iran will gain access to billions of dollars of oil revenues trapped in South Korea under US sanctions.</p><p> US and European officials have told Iran that if there is de-escalation of tensions over the summer, they would be open to broader talks later this year, including on Iran&#39;s nuclear program.</p><p> “If Iran were to take de-escalating steps with respect to their nuclear ambitions again, that would all be to the good,” John Kirby, a spokesman for the White House National Security Council, said Friday. “We&#39;re not in active negotiations about the nuclear program, but certainly, those sorts of steps…would be welcome.”</p><p> For the Biden administration, the hope is to avoid any major crisis with Tehran in the lead-up to next year&#39;s presidential elections. Critics in Washington and elsewhere say the US is preparing to reward Iran for taking US citizens hostage and for a minor pause in its nuclear work while Tehran ramps up regional threats and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/iran-expands-military-aid-to-russia-amid-war-in-ukraine-u-s-says-e1c819cd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">supplies military assistance to Russia</a> for its <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraines-sea-drones-alter-balance-of-power-in-black-sea-391cebee?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">war against Ukraine</a> . </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=3EF0C42D-95E2-4D6C-A3B3-D34D9D232BB9&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Firan-slows-buildup-of-near-weapons-grade-enriched-uranium-492df473&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Iran has freed five Americans from a notorious Tehran prison as it sought to have billions in frozen revenue released in return, US and Iranian officials said. Secretary of State Antony Blinken said sanctions against Iran will continue to be enforced. Photo: Cliff Owen/AP<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>Since the US left the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-to-withdraw-u-s-from-iran-accord-1525800212?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">2015 Iranian nuclear accord</a> , which lifted international sanctions on Tehran in exchange for strict but temporary limitations on its nuclear work, Tehran has massively expanded its program. The Biden administration sought to revive the nuclear pact when it took office, but those talks broke down last year.</p><p> Among the most worrying parts of its work for Western officials is Tehran&#39;s production of 60% enriched uranium, which US officials say could be turned into enough weapons-grade material for a nuclear bomb in less than two weeks.</p><p> Iran says its nuclear program is for peaceful aims only.</p><h3> Moves appear intentional</h3><p> US officials had hoped Tehran would stop accumulating 60% enriched uranium as one of a series of de-escalatory steps from both sides, which included the prisoners deal.</p><p> According to the people, Iran has diluted a small amount of 60% enriched uranium in recent weeks and slowed the rate at which it is accumulating new material. Iran&#39;s stockpile has grown since the 114 kilograms of highly enriched uranium Iran was recorded having in May, but it could easily dilute more of the 60% it has produced to get back to that level. It isn&#39;t yet clear if Tehran plans to do that.</p><p> Iran was adding just short of 9 kilograms of 60% to its stockpile on average between February and May.</p><p> The United Nations atomic agency is expected to release its next report on Iran&#39;s nuclear program in late August or early September.</p><p> While Iran&#39;s production rate of enriched uranium can fluctuate for a number of technical reasons—including maintenance work at one of its two nuclear facilities—the fact that Iran has diluted some highly enriched uranium strongly suggests the slower accumulation of 60% material is intentional.</p><p> Nonetheless, even if it does stop accumulating 60% material, Tehran has enough of the material for at least two nuclear bombs. US officials said this year Iran could field a nuclear weapon within several months.</p><p> Iran&#39;s mission to the International Atomic Energy Agency didn&#39;t immediately respond to a request for comment. Neither did the IAEA.</p><p> Following <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-launches-quiet-diplomatic-push-with-iran-to-cool-tensions-2f45af3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">secret indirect talks this spring involving senior US and Iranian officials,</a> Biden administration officials set out several steps they hoped Tehran would take to lower tensions. In addition to stopping the accumulation of 60% material, they said they hoped Iran would show better cooperation with the IAEA and stop attacks by Iran or its proxies on US forces and personnel.</p><p> In exchange, Iran was set to win access to some $6 billion in energy-sales revenue frozen in South Korea and possibly other moneys from the International Monetary Fund.</p><h3> Risk of delays</h3><p> While the Biden administration has largely given up hopes of reviving the 2015 nuclear deal with Iran, US officials continue to say publicly they are seeking to avert a nuclear crisis through diplomacy. If the de-escalation effort bears fruit, the two sides could meet on the sidelines of the United Nations General Assembly in September and map out further talks.</p><p> This week&#39;s release from jail of four American prisoners was the first step in a two-track plan, according to US and European officials. A fifth US citizen is under house arrest.</p><p> In a first stage, the diplomats said the American detainees would be released from prison in exchange for the transfer of up to $6 billion in Iranian oil revenue from South Korea to Switzerland, which represents US interests in Iran. As a second step, likely to take several weeks, the US citizens would be permitted to leave Iran once the Iranian money from South Korea reaches banks in Qatar, which Iran can access but Washington keeps under close watch.</p><p> US officials warned this week that they were still working on moving the South Korean funds and cautioned that the eventual release of the detainees could be delayed by disagreements in Tehran or the emergence of new flashpoints with Iran.</p><p> US officials insisted that Iran would only be able to use the funds to buy food and medical goods for humanitarian purposes. Critics say the money would free up other Iranian government funds to be used for more nefarious purposes.</p><p> Just as the prisoner issue and the enrichment of near-weapons-grade material have started to move in the right direction, there have been no serious attacks on US forces in the region by Tehran <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/drone-strike-that-killed-u-s-contractor-in-syria-was-launched-by-iran-backed-militia-in-iraq-3a5e368a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">or its proxies since late March when a US contractor was killed</a> .</p><p> However, in the last couple of weeks, the US <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-deploys-advanced-f-35-jets-destroyer-to-middle-east-to-brush-back-iranian-forces-7d9a92cf?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">has rushed planes, ships and Marines to the Gulf</a> because of the Iranian threat to shipping in the Gulf, an unusual and substantial deployment.</p><p> “There is selective de-escalation in some areas and escalation in other areas and I think, in general, both sides are likely seeking a lowering of tensions but they have different definitions of the scope of de-escalation,” said Henry Rome, senior fellow at the Washington Institute for Near East Policy.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Michael R. Gordon in Washington contributed to this article.</p><p> Write to Laurence Norman at <a href="mailto:laurence.norman@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">laurence.norman@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 17:17:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/iran-slows-buildup-of-near-weapons-grade-enriched-uranium-492df473</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/iran-slows-buildup-of-near-weapons-grade-enriched-uranium-492df473<author><![CDATA[Laurence Norman]]></author><category> kwexclusive</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>Armed Forces</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国际制裁</category><category>Nuclear Weapons Programs</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>Weapons Programs</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>armed forces</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国际制裁</category><category>nuclear weapons programs</category><category>政治</category><category>weapons programs </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[African Force to Reverse Niger Coup Could Take Months]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Regional bloc called for activating standby force to restore order but appears to waffle on its intentions <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001128355"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="550" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834025?width=860&amp;height=550" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Niger&#39;s President Mohamed Bazoum was deposed in a coup late last month.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: EVELYN HOCKSTEIN/REUTERS </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001128355"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/michael-m-phillips" itemprop="url" rel="author">Michael M. Phillips</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/benoit-faucon" itemprop="url" rel="author">Benoit Faucon</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 11, 2023 11:50 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/african-force-to-reverse-niger-coup-could-take-months-95962335"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> NAIROBI—Leaders of 11 West African nations this week reinforced their threat to use force to reverse <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-president-us-fumble-russia-africa-86cf1454-33d18bc?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Niger&#39;s coup d&#39;état</a> , but Western and African officials say it could take months to attempt such an ambitious operation.</p><p> Leaders of the Economic Community of West African States, Ecowas, activated a regional standby force Thursday and ordered its deployment “to restore constitutional order” in Niger, where last month top military officers deposed elected President Mohamed Bazoum.</p><p> The West African bloc appeared to waffle on its intentions, however. Its chairman, Nigerian President Bola Ahmed Tinubu, referred to the use of force as a “last resort” and Ecowas President Omar Touray stressed the group&#39;s “continued commitment to the restoration of constitutional order through peaceful means.”</p><p> The mixed messages left US officials scrambling to figure out whether Ecowas was bluffing with its threat of force; immediately after the coup, Ecowas gave the junta a week to cede power, but <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/deadline-for-niger-coup-leaders-to-back-down-passes-without-intervention-c6e85794?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the deadline passed with no action</a> .</p><p> “Everyone is puzzling over the recent Ecowas statement,” said a senior US defense official. “They haven&#39;t moved forces and haven&#39;t taken many steps to prepare for the military intervention.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=7F7AB6E6-CE60-46D3-B0B7-C075C1006060&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fafrican-force-to-reverse-niger-coup-could-take-months-95962335&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Coup leaders in Niger announced a closure of its airspace, causing flights to reroute around the country. It comes as the Sunday deadline set by other West African countries for the military junta to back down passed. Photo: Flightradar24.com<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>Pro-coup counterthreats from <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-africa-u-s-trained-militaries-are-ousting-civilian-governments-in-coups-11649505601?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Mali, Burkina Faso and Guinea</a> —run by military juntas who themselves came to power by force—may be deterring the Ecowas bloc from taking action, the US official said. The extensive combat experience of Niger&#39;s armed forces that now hold power, some of which are among the most effective in the region, might also be giving Ecowas pause, the US official said.</p><p> A top army commander from one Ecowas member state predicted it would take six months to ready any intervention to reverse Niger&#39;s coup. The Ecowas standby force is one of five such regional forces across Africa, but they exist more on paper than in reality until called upon to intervene.</p><p> The army commander described the West African standby force as “an empty shell” that member countries would have to fill with troops and equipment.</p><p> “There is no assembled, mustered military force standing-by somewhere ready to immediately deploy,” Paul Williams, professor of international affairs at the George Washington University, wrote on the social-media platform X, formerly known as Twitter.</p><p> The Nigerien junta, meanwhile, shows no sign of backing down. Talks this week between Victoria Nuland, the US acting deputy secretary of state, and Brig. Gen. Moussa Salaou Barmou, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-us-trained-general-65b5ecd6?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Niger&#39;s new chief of defense staff</a> , produced no apparent movement toward a return to elected government. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="495" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834019?width=700&amp;height=495" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Supporters of Niger&#39;s military junta in the country&#39;s capital, Niamey.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: luff/Shutterstock</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Barmou didn&#39;t respond Friday to a request for comment on how the junta plans to respond to the Ecowas threat.</p><p> The deposed president, Bazoum, his wife and 21-year-old son have been confined to his residence in Niamey, the country&#39;s capital, since his own presidential guard initiated the uprising.</p><p> Over the past two days, the junta has beefed up security to 70 guards around Bazoum, said a Western official and people who have spoken to him. Guards have also flown a drone over the residence in response to unsubstantiated rumors that French soldiers had entered the compound, the people said.</p><p> In a phone call with French President Emmanuel Macron, Bazoum reported the junta had cut off power to the residence and warned his family would soon run out of water, according to the Western official and people who have spoken with Bazoum. He issued the same warning in a phone call to Secretary of State Antony Blinken, according to the people close to Bazoum. A doctor who had been conducting daily medical checks is no longer allowed to see Bazoum and his family, according to the people who have spoken to him. Nuland said the junta denied her requests to visit the deposed president. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="477" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834020?width=700&amp;height=477" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A market in Niamey. The US has 1,100 troops in Niger.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Agence France-Presse/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The European Union “reiterates it is deeply concerned at the deteriorating conditions in which the president is being detained,” EU foreign policy chief</p> Josep Borrell posted online Friday.<p></p><p> France, the former colonial power in Niger, described Bazoum&#39;s incarceration as a “kidnapping.” France has refused to withdraw its 1,500 troops from the country, where they are fighting al Qaeda and Islamic State militants, on the grounds that Bazoum has neither resigned nor severed Niger&#39;s security accords with France.</p><p> The US has 1,100 troops in Niger, stationed at two drone bases and three commando posts, to train and support Nigerien special forces, including Barmou. Until Bazoum&#39;s overthrow, the US had very close ties to Niger&#39;s military and considered the country a bedrock of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-upends-u-s-security-plans-in-west-africa-handing-russia-an-opportunity-8dcf6679?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">its counterterrorism policy in West Africa</a> .</p><p> Should the State Department declare Bazoum&#39;s overthrow a coup, US law would require the withdrawal of most military aid.</p><p> Write to Michael M. Phillips at <a href="mailto:Michael.Phillips@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Michael.Phillips@wsj.com</a> and Benoit Faucon at <a href="mailto:benoit.faucon@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">benoit.faucon@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 15:50:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/african-force-to-reverse-niger-coup-could-take-months-95962335</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/african-force-to-reverse-niger-coup-could-take-months-95962335<author><![CDATA[Michael M. PhillipsBenoit Faucon]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>叛乱</category><category>Armed Forces</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Omar Touray</category><category> Paul Williams</category><category>维多利亚·纽兰</category><category>Moussa Salaou Barmou</category><category> Mohamed Bazoum</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>叛乱</category><category>armed forces</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[China’s Options for Retaliation Are Few After U.S. Investment Ban]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>分析师表示，鉴于资金流动不对称和国内经济疲软，北京不太可能采取美国的限制措施<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001127971"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834066?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Beijing is seeking to sustain a diplomatic thaw with Washington.</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：托马斯·彼得/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001127971"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/liza-lin" itemprop="url" rel="author">Liza Lin</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dan-strumpf" itemprop="url" rel="author">Dan Strumpf</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 11 日上午 8:40（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-options-for-retaliation-are-few-after-u-s-investment-ban-f539102e"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>中国不太可能因<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-to-ban-some-investments-in-china-71f519d6?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">拜登政府对某些中国科技公司实施新的投资禁令而</a>对美国进行反击。分析人士表示，这是因为北京方面发动猛烈攻击的能力和愿望都有限。</p><p>美国科技公司对中国投资的依赖程度不像中国科技公司对美国资本的依赖程度。他们表示，中国还在努力应对宏观经济状况恶化和投资者信心下降的问题，这使其不太可能升级经济僵局。 On the political front, Beijing is also seeking to sustain a diplomatic thaw with Washington.</p><p> This week, the US issued an executive order banning Americans from investing in Chinese companies developing advanced semiconductors and quantum computers and requires American investors to notify Washington about investments in other types of semiconductors and artificial intelligence. The limits, which come into place next year, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-and-china-poised-to-drift-further-apart-after-investment-ban-1e37427d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">amp up the race</a> between the two major rivals over who controls the next generation of critical technology.</p><p>中国商务部周四表示，美国的行为偏离了市场规范，美国正在扰乱全球供应链和贸易。中国外交部谴责这些举动是美国“公然的经济胁迫和科技欺凌”，并补充说中国将采取行动保护自己的权利。</p><p>尽管有这些言论，但分析人士和商界人士认为，对外投资措施不足以改变双方都在努力改善的紧张双边关系。中国很早就知道此类措施即将出台，一些人表示，新规定没有许多人担心的那么严格，而且目标范围更窄——至少目前的形式是这样。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=607DAEAC-FDF3-4309-B753-4A08C846B405&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fchinas-options-for-retaliation-are-few-after-u-s-investment-ban-f539102e&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">从喷气式飞机到电动汽车再到超级计算机，《华尔街日报》与不同的行业和技术专家讨论了两国在设计、工程和战略方面的匹配情况。照片插图：迈克尔·塔布和盖蒂图片社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>相反，北京更有可能在其他领域进行报复，例如<strong>&nbsp;</strong>对中国具有重大影响力和控制权的关键材料（如稀土或特定矿物）实施更多出口限制。</p><p> President Biden, speaking at a political fundraiser on Thursday, referred to China&#39;s weakening economy and the problem that poses for its leaders. “China is a ticking time bomb in many cases,” Biden said, noting China&#39;s high youth unemployment and an aging workforce.</p><p>不过，他表示，他希望与北京建立“理性关系”。 “我不想伤害中国，”他在犹他州说。</p><p> In July, China set <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-restricts-exports-of-two-metals-used-in-high-performance-chips-a649402b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">export restrictions on gallium and germanium</a> , two minerals the US and experts have said are <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-latest-export-controls-prompt-countries-to-explore-supply-chain-diversification-318e74d1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">key to producing semiconductors</a> , missile systems and solar cells. Beijing&#39;s move was viewed by experts as retaliation against <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-considers-new-curbs-on-ai-chip-exports-to-china-56b17feb?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">US export restrictions</a> aimed at curbing Beijing&#39;s high-technology industries.</p><p> “我们预计中国会采取一些高调但不会升级的行动进行报复，”风险咨询公司欧亚集团地质技术业务主管陆晓萌表示。她预测，当局将对涉及美国公司的并购交易做出严厉的判断，或者尝试进一步限制中国的出口管制。</p><p>卢表示，该命令的直接影响有限，因为美国已经对这些行业实施了事先限制，而且中美之间的跨境投资流量已处于历史低位。她补充说，今年第一季度，美国风险投资和私募股权公司对中国的投资锐减至约 4 亿美元，而 2021 年的峰值约为 350 亿美元。</p><p>新加坡国立大学政治学副教授贾伊恩·庄 (Ja Ian Chong) 表示，从长远来看，中国将加大寻找受限制的美国技术替代品的力度，包括利用代理购买或投资可以接触到的外国公司。等关键技术。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834073?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Treasury Secretary Janet Yellen, with Chinese Vice Premier He Lifeng in Beijing last month, said the US doesn&#39;t intend to threaten China&#39;s development.</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：POOL/来自路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>美国和中国是否会采取新一波针锋相对的措施是各国政府和专家正在关注的问题。</p><p>继美国之前采取的措施之后，中国对华盛顿进行了反击，有时力度更为有限。</p><p> A year ago, when then-House Speaker <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/nancy-pelosi">Nancy Pelosi</a> visited Taiwan, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-boasts-of-ability-to-blockade-taiwan-as-military-exercises-continue-11659695158?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">China reacted</a> with days of large-scale military exercises, halted cooperation with Washington on issues including climate and froze some military contacts. 2018年和2019年，由于两国在贸易战期间都征收关税，北京方面更难对华盛顿的措施进行相应的报复，因为它从美国进口的产品减少了</p><p>The US is a large and mature market for venture capital and money flows between the two countries are asymmetrical.</p><p>新的行政命令发布之际，拜登政府再次努力与北京重新接触，以制止长达数月的不断恶化的关系。</p><p> Among recent efforts include last month&#39;s visits to China by Secretary of State Antony Blinken</p> and Treasury Secretary Janet Yellen.访问期间， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/yellen-trip-aids-fragile-effort-by-u-s-china-to-keep-talking-9b78ea55?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">耶伦试图保证</a>美国不会威胁中国的整体发展，任何行动都仅以国家安全为由。<p></p><p>周四，中国官方媒体强调了她的言论与新投资限制之间的矛盾。中国官方媒体新华社的一篇社论指责美国在美国高级官员访问中国后推出这些措施，并向当局保证他们无意与中国脱钩，从而发出了相互矛盾的信号。</p><p>尽管新规则已经激怒了北京，但“拜登有意识地努力降低美中关系的温度，”杰富瑞投资银行的技术分析师爱迪生·李周四在一份研究报告中写道。</p><p>更广泛地说，其他人认为，鉴于中国的经济困境，中国兑现其威胁的意愿有限。本周公布的数据显示，中国经济可能陷入<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-slips-into-deflation-in-warning-sign-for-world-economy-bbefb179?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">通货紧缩周期，</a> 7月份消费者价格出现自2021年以来的首次下跌。这加剧了其他经济困境的迹象，包括<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinese-exports-fall-at-steepest-pace-since-february-2020-e930246b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">出口下降</a>、 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-youth-unemployment-xi-jobs-522028c5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">青年失业率</a>高企和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/country-garden-chinas-largest-surviving-developer-sinks-into-debt-crisis-2a525173?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">房地产市场长期低迷。暴跌</a>。</p><p>战略与国际中心研究贸易和技术的高级研究员艾米丽·本森 (Emily Benson) 表示：“鉴于中国目前不稳定的宏观经济状况，他们确实不能冒进一步报复的风险，从而阻止第三国在中国的投资。”学习。</p><p>此外，她表示拜登政府的规则仍处于草案阶段。她说，考虑到行业和政府之间通常在任何此类法规最终实施之前都会反复进行，最终规则的形成和实施可能需要长达一年的时间。</p><p> “没有什么是一成不变的，”她说，并将拟议的规则描述为白宫的“愿望清单”。</p><p>写信给丽莎·林<a href="mailto:liza.lin@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">(liza.lin@wsj.com)</a>和丹·斯特朗普夫 ( <a href="mailto:Dan.Strumpf@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Dan.Strumpf@ws​​j.com)</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 12:40:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-options-for-retaliation-are-few-after-us-investment-ban-f539102e</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-options-for-retaliation-are-few-after-us-investment-ban-f539102e<author><![CDATA[Liza LinDan Strumpf]]></author><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Here’s What a $5 Million Retirement Looks Like in America]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>退休人员公开他们的财务生活以及他们如何度过时间和金钱<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832718/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="身着粉红色衣服的退休人员帕特·弗雷 (Pat Frey) 经常与朋友一起在大自然中散步。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>身着粉红色衣服的退休人员帕特·弗雷 (Pat Frey) 经常与朋友一起在大自然中散步。丽贝卡·斯坦普夫 (Rebecca Stumpf) 的《华尔街日报》<span>丽贝卡·斯坦普夫 (Rebecca Stumpf) 的《华尔街日报》</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001122102"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001122102"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/veronica-dagher" itemprop="url" rel="author">维罗妮卡·达格尔</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/anne-tergesen" itemprop="url" rel="author">安妮·特格森</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 11 日上午 5:30 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/heres-what-a-5-million-retirement-looks-like-in-america-1abc76d9"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>多少钱都无法让退休后无忧无虑，但 500 万美元可能就差不多了。</p><p>很少有美国人能够在 401(k) 计划和个人退休账户中存下接近这一金额的钱。根据<a href="https://www.ebri.org/" target="_blank" class="icon none">员工福利研究所</a>使用 2019 年消费者财务调查对退休账户进行的分析，500 万美元的退休储蓄金使您跻身前 0.1% 的家庭之列。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="1092" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/d663f044-8f28-4ec7-8377-2302a6c566d6-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>为了了解 500 万美元可以在退休后购买什么，我们采访了全国各地拥有该金额储蓄的退休人员。</p><p>大多数人从未想过会成为百万富翁，但从职业生涯的早期就勤于储蓄。</p><p>尽管与<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/retirement-under-1-million-america-846a6ab6?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">我们介绍的许多退休人员</a>相比，他们不太担心自己的钱花光了，但他们并不都过着奢侈的生活。有些人已经很多年没有买新衣服了。其他人继续兼职工作。</p><p>他们在环球旅行上挥霍无度，但像大多数年长的美国人一样，担心自己的健康和家人。</p><p>仅靠金钱也无法解决退休人员面临的另一个问题：如何在人生的这一章中找到目的和意义？ </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/archibald/1JhIu4HsU3kUrK8q6t8nArRD6-qm34M9iySjy14qk7vc-chapter-1.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>保罗·谢姆韦尔 (Paul Shemwell) 在驾驶商用飞机和喷气式战斗机四十年后于 12 月退休。</p><p>尽管这位 65 岁的老人感觉自己的财务状况很安全，已经攒下了约 610 万美元，但他还没有制定接下来的飞行计划。</p><p>对于这位前飞行员来说，这种随意的态度是一个巨大的改变，他在空军的 13 年中磨练了自己的战略思维能力。他的服役经历也教会他仔细权衡自己的选择，这一理念指导着他的退休生活。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/2decacce-5119-4fbc-9b6f-3b2bd857ad6d.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/LUV" class="">西南航空公司</a>工作 28 年后，他不再乘坐飞机<span class="company-name-type">，</span>但旅行仍然是他的热情所在。他计划今年秋天进行四次旅行，这种旅行癖让他每月花费约 3,000 美元。他每月还要花费大约 9,000 美元用于财产税、房屋和汽车保险等费用。</p><p>他的一天通常从锻炼或网球课开始。作为一名狂热的滑雪爱好者，他已经购买了本赛季的通行证，并计划每年至少进行一次水肺潜水旅行。</p><p>谢姆韦尔拒绝了几份重返驾驶舱的工作机会，部分原因是他不需要钱。</p><p>他计划在达到完全退休年龄后领取<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/social-security-payment-increase-cola-2024-retirement-a3fce38e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">社会保障</a>，这将使年收入增加约 40,000 美元。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/173863f5-743a-4d58-a219-b57a7e01cbf8.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>空巢老人的生活是另一个巨大的变化。他的儿子是大学二年级学生，女儿今年秋天开始上大学。谢姆韦尔已离婚并拥有共同监护权，他表示，他将深入参与孩子的生活作为首要任务。</p><p>他的航班时刻表使他能够灵活地参加孩子们的大部分网球和足球比赛。现在他们都在上学了，他想去看看他们比赛。</p><p>谢姆韦尔现在花更多的时间和他的朋友在一起，大多数工作日都会和他们一起吃午餐。</p><p>他不是一个活跃的交易者，但仍关注市场。他的投资组合<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/it-isnt-just-boomers-lots-of-older-americans-are-stock-obsessed-ca069e1a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">95%是股票</a>，大部分是指数基金，还有<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AAPL" class="">苹果</a>等少数个股<span class="company-name-type">。</span> </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832732?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">保罗·谢姆韦尔最近再次开始打网球。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的杰克·汤普森</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>他的父亲已经 90 多岁了，所以谢姆韦尔并不担心他大量的股票配置。</p><p> “我的计划是继续量入为出或量入为出，保持投资并为我的孩子们留下一些东西，”他说。</p><p>谢姆韦尔在休斯顿的房屋抵押贷款还剩大约 30 万美元。他的再融资利率为 2.99%，因此他并不急于偿还债务。</p><p>他驾驶的是一辆 2016 款英菲尼迪，行驶里程约为 80,000 英里。这辆车以及他为女儿购买的二手奔驰都是付费的。他每月全额支付信用卡账单。</p><p> “我喜欢让事情变得简单，”他说。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/archibald/1JhIu4HsU3kUrK8q6t8nArRD6-qm34M9iySjy14qk7vc-chapter-2.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Jay Myer 积累了足够的积蓄，可以在 2020 年提前退休，因为他在 401(k) 计划中缴纳了数十年的最高缴款。</p><p> 25 岁时，迈尔读了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/vanguards-founder-a-force-of-nature-11547812685?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">先锋创始人约翰·博格尔 (John Bogle)</a>写的一本支持低成本指数基金的书。他也按照著名选股家彼得·林奇的建议购买了个股，“买你所知道的”。对于现年 61 岁的迈尔来说，这意味着科技股和与他进行软件交易的公司的股票，其中包括家得<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/HD" class="">宝 (Home Depot)</a> <span class="company-name-type">，</span>他在几十年前以每股 3 美元的分割调整价格购买了该公司。</p><p> “我当时还很年轻，才读到有关退休的文章，但这对我来说很有意义。如果你降低投资成本，你就会保留更多的利润，”迈尔说，他的退休账户投资于七只先锋指数基金。</p><p>他和 60 岁的妻子安妮塔 (Anita) 开着二手车，并严格遵守预算，以便 Myer 从 22 岁起就可以向他的 401(k) 账户缴纳最高年度限额。安妮塔 (Anita) 一直担任牙科保健员，直到 2000 年他们的第二个儿子出生。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/d872ec8a-8e9f-4719-9763-3d49c3645f1b.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>迈尔说，他决定提前退休的部分原因是他的继父是一位小企业主，喜欢旅行和与孙辈共度时光。</p><p> “他向我展示了你可以放下工作场所并重新认识自己，”迈尔说。</p><p>起初，失去稳定的薪水是很可怕的。当 2020 年市场暴跌时，他仔细检查了这对夫妇的每一次购买，甚至餐巾纸，但很快意识到，考虑到他们的健康储蓄，这样做是没有必要的。</p><p>这对夫妇现在拥有 420 万美元，一半在退休账户，一半在应税账户。</p><p>这对夫妇利用最近出售亚特兰大房屋的收益，以 925,000 美元在卡里购买了一套房子，距离他们经常见到的大儿子的家人有 2 英里。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832750?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">迈尔斯夫妇喜欢烹饪、园艺和旅行，并计划改进他们的新家。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的 Kate Medley</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>他们每年花费约 130,000 美元，其中包括 5,000 美元的财产税。他们每个月在食品上花费约 700 美元，在健康保险上花费 1,000 美元。 （由于他们目前用现金储备支出，这对夫妇的应税收入足够低，有资格获得保险补贴。）</p><p>为了最大化他每月的福利，迈尔表示他会等到 70 岁才领取社会保障。</p><p>这对夫妇曾考虑出售一些个股，以将更多资金投入债券，但由于利润所欠的资本利得税而打消了念头。他们决定把最大的赢家留给他们的两个儿子。</p><p>迈尔斯夫妇每年的旅行预算约为 20,000 美元，他们正计划今年去西班牙旅行，他们的小儿子今年就住在那里。</p><p>两人都喜欢烹饪和园艺。迈尔说他很享受自由自在的时间。</p><p> “现在我有了更多的时间，我学会了拥抱无聊，放慢脚步，有时接受读书或骑自行车就足够了，”他说。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/archibald/1JhIu4HsU3kUrK8q6t8nArRD6-qm34M9iySjy14qk7vc-chapter-3.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>对于胡亨利博士来说，工作是实现令人满意的退休生活的一部分。</p><p>这位加利福尼亚州欧文市的外科医生过去每周工作长达 80 个小时，但现在他在假期期间兼职工作。 “我真的很喜欢旅行，”72 岁的胡说。</p><p> Hwu 是一名来自台湾的移民，他说他和已故的妻子于 1979 年来到美国。在芝加哥学习了五年外科手术并于 1986 年在密歇根州完成结直肠外科奖学金后，Hwu 搬到了南加州，他和妻子在那里抚养了三个孩子。</p><p>在达到医疗实践规定的 65 岁强制退休年龄之前，Hwu 开始阅读有关退休的书籍（他说还有《华尔街日报》的文章）。他开始打高尔夫球和泡菜球，还买了一把吉他，重拾了自医学院以来他几乎没有时间从事的一项爱好。</p><p>但 2016 年退休后，他错过了工作并开始接受以前诊所的任务。</p><p>每天早上，他都会问自己这一天要做什么。 “我不喜欢那种感觉，”胡说，他的妻子在他退休后不久就去世了。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832859?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Henry Hwu 博士于 2016 年正式退休，但在不旅行时继续兼职工作。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的 Ryan Young</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>胡每年旅行长达三个月，去台湾看望他 98 岁的母亲，或者游览苏格兰、法国、德国、日本和瑞士，他曾在那里给朋友买了很多巧克力，结果行李箱都坏了。</p><p> Hwu经常带着他的吉他。最近在伦敦时，他给了一位街头音乐家 20 英镑让他让位，以便他可以演奏 Everly Brothers 的《Let It Be Me》。 “我不知道人们是否喜欢它，但有一位观众站在我面前，”胡说。</p><p>胡仍然喜欢参加医学会议和阅读医学期刊。</p><p>在 2017 年的一次会议上，他遇到了洛斯阿拉莫斯一家乡村医院唯一的外科医生 NM Hwu，现在大多数月份都会前往洛斯阿拉莫斯为外科医生接班几天。在那里，他喜欢徒步旅行并拜访在阿尔伯克基担任会计师的儿子。</p><p>在家时，Hwu 会去上吉他课，并经常见到他的女儿和小孙女。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/f3b9dd2c-d95e-4677-81b1-f14a149509ca.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>他的房子价值150万美元。他拥有第二套房子，价值 120 万美元，每月租金为 3,500 美元。他每套房子欠约 50 万美元，但并不急于偿还抵押贷款，因为利率低于 3%。</p><p> Hwu 将其退休账户中超过 100 万美元的资金几乎全部投资于股票基金和个股，包括苹果、<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MSFT" class="company-name">微软</a>和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NVDA" class="">英伟达</a><span class="company-name-type">。</span></p><p>他每月领取 2,700 美元的社会保障福利，从 65 岁开始领取。他每年领取约 13 万美元的养老金，去年从每日工作中赚取约 30 万美元。</p><p>旅行是他的大手笔，每年花费 10 万美元。其他开支约为每月 4,000 美元，这还不包括他的抵押贷款付款。</p><p>他每年还支付 6,800 美元的长期护理保险。</p><p> “我妈妈活到了 98 岁，我有一天会无法照顾自己，”他说。 “我想减轻孩子们的负担。” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/archibald/1JhIu4HsU3kUrK8q6t8nArRD6-qm34M9iySjy14qk7vc-chapter-4.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>在成长过程中，鲍勃·弗雷（Bob Frey）从未想过自己会成为百万富翁退休。</p><p>从西点军校毕业后，他在现役期间获得了硕士学位，然后通过陆军预备役奖学金和退伍军人法案获得了兽医学位。他担任预备役军官 26 年，60 岁退休。他从 30 多岁开始就用尽了退休计划缴款。</p><p>日子有时很艰难，比如当他借了大约 15 万美元开办兽医诊所时。多年来，他卖掉了三项业务，其中包括两家兽医诊所。他说，这些退出极大地增加了他的价值。</p><p>如今，80 岁的鲍勃和 75 岁的妻子帕特·弗雷已经存下了约 610 万美元，其中几乎一半投资于个人退休账户。</p><p>弗雷每年领取 60,000 美元的军事养老金，加上每年约 14,000 美元的退伍军人伤残补偿金，因为他在越南服役后出现了听力损失。这对夫妇从社会保障金中总共领取了约 56,000 美元。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/b82deef5-2fa7-4359-8b0c-802cb8012644.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> “我们拥有的钱比我们一生花的还要多，”他说。</p><p>这对夫妇结婚已有 30 多年，育有 5 个成年子女。 20 世纪 90 年代初，他们搬到了蒙大拿州博兹曼，寻求新的开始并更接近大自然。帕特继续她的护理生涯，鲍勃接受重新培训，成为一名认证财务规划师。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>您为退休制定了哪些财务计划？请通过下面的表格告诉我们您的经历。</em></p></div></div><p>弗雷家族尽管富有，但通常都会避免其装饰。鲍勃说他已经大约 20 年没有买过新的运动外套了。这对夫妇住在蒙大拿州，他们说他们不太用得着正装，宁愿穿着牛仔裤和运动鞋到处走动。帕特经常和朋友一起去大自然散步。</p><p>弗雷夫妇预计将花费约 150 万美元来帮助支付他们九个孙辈的教育费用。他们每年还向他们最喜欢的慈善机构（包括他们的教堂）捐赠大约 40,000 美元。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832798?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">鲍勃·弗雷 (Bob Frey) 在世界各地和离家不远的加拉廷河 (Gallatin River) 飞钓。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Rebecca Stumpf for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>这对夫妇没有债务，也没有过多调整他们的投资，其中大约 70% 投资于股票基金。鲍勃说，他们死后可能会向慈善机构留下约 100 万美元。</p><p>弗雷夫妇也很重视旅行，每年会拨出约 35,000 美元用于环游世界。他们曾五次访问新西兰，鲍勃经常将他对飞钓的热爱与阿拉斯加、墨西哥和南美洲的旅行结合起来。</p><p>他们还喜欢与朋友单独旅行。帕特经常与朋友一起前往欧洲和加拉帕戈斯群岛。她跳过了鲍勃的狩猎之旅。</p><p> “我不想睡在帐篷里，把麋鹿带出树林，”她说。</p><p>写信给 Veronica Dagher <a href="mailto:Veronica.Dagher@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">（Veronica.Dagher@wsj.com）</a>和 Anne Tergesen（ <a href="mailto:anne.tergesen@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">anne.tergesen@wsj.com）</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/2d22c5e9-a490-4c14-9b85-792395763a6e.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/newsroom-feedback/89ceea19-a743-45d2-8530-c974dc040b2e.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/heres-what-a-5-million-retirement-looks-like-in-america-1abc76d9</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/heres-what-a-5-million-retirement-looks-like-in-america-1abc76d9<author><![CDATA[Veronica DagherAnne Tergesen]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>gfx-contrib</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>老年健康</category><category>人口健康</category><category>健康</category><category>个人退休账户</category><category>个人财务</category><category>退休计划</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>老年健康</category><category>人口健康</category><category>健康</category><category>个人退休账户</category><category>个人财务</category><category>退休计划</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Amazon Wants to Deliver Your Order Without a Box]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The retail giant is reducing packaging on millions of deliveries <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832983/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="Amazon can reduce its packaging in part because it has built out its distribution network including fulfillment centers like this one in Melville, N.Y.,  to reduce the distance its packages need to travel to their final destinations." referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Amazon can reduce its packaging in part because it has built out its distribution network including fulfillment centers like this one in Melville, NY, to reduce the distance its packages need to travel to their final destinations. Johnny Milano/Bloomberg News <span>Johnny Milano/Bloomberg News</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001124909"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001124909"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sebastian-herrera" itemprop="url" rel="author">Sebastian Herrera</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 11 日上午 5:30 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/amazon-deliver-prime-speed-packaging-a616a135"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> Millions of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AMZN" class="company-name">Amazon</a> orders are arriving on doorsteps across the US without any extra packaging. A new television may sit in the manufacturer&#39;s box at the door. A blender appears as if it were picked off a store shelf. The same for a box of baby wipes or trash bags.</p><p> The change represents the next frontier in the tech giant&#39;s overhaul of its delivery processes, one Chief Executive Andy Jassy hopes will appeal to customers who are put off by the volume of Amazon-branded boxes they receive and discard every week.</p><p> The company in the past year revamped its logistics network, enabling faster and more efficient deliveries. Eliminating or reducing packaging has become increasingly important for the company to maintain its dominance, reduce costs and reach its goals related to its climate impact.</p><p> “The recognition by a number of senior leaders was just that this is becoming more and more important,” said Pat Lindner, who Amazon hired last year as its first vice president of packaging and innovation. “There&#39;s a significant need for our company to take the next step in innovation around packaging.”</p><p> About 11% of items that the company delivers now arrive without extra packaging, or what the company calls “ships in own container,” Amazon said. Customers typically are able to choose at checkout if they want extra packaging or prefer their order without it. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832954?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> At its testing facility in Sumner, Wash. , Amazon tests if packages can survive delivery unscathed. This Compression Tester simulates stacking in vertical compression, explained Rett Bruce, a senior lab technician.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Kholood Eid for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Challenges range from practical to emotional. Amazon needs to help its suppliers create packaging that is both sturdy enough to ship on its own while not adding extra material to undercut its whole purpose of doing away with packaging. And it needs to determine whether customers might not want to have, for instance, a giant package of toilet paper sitting on their doorsteps for all their neighbors to see.</p><p> Amazon is using its formidable clout with packaged-goods companies and other suppliers and vendors, as well as incentives, to get them to improve their packaging to survive shipping. Vendors on the site, for example, can get incentives to eliminate the extra packaging layer.</p><p> While Amazon is losing some branding power from cutting back on its signature brown boxes, it is betting that the elimination of extra packaging will create goodwill with its customers, many of whom, it said, have asked the company for such changes.</p><p> “Sometimes you get a giant box with a very little item that, quite frankly, wasn&#39;t breakable in the first place. And you wonder why they used all that material,” said Kenneth Levine, a 76-year-old in River Vale, NJ, who said he receives Amazon packages about once a week. He has yet to notice the option to reduce packaging at checkout, but said he would be open to it for reasonable and non-fragile items, like books. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=C72EA178-F0CA-46FE-B63D-3CE629CAF70C&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Famazon-deliver-prime-speed-packaging-a616a135&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> The pandemic has changed the way we shop. More people buying things online means more people returning things, too. WSJ&#39;s Dalvin Brown explains how some companies are leveraging gig workers to make those returns for you. Photo illustration: David Fang<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>There is also some chatter online that leaving deliveries visible could lead to other issues.</p><p> “The manufacturer&#39;s box doesn&#39;t have anything holding it shut, and isn&#39;t designed to have a shipping label slapped on it,” a user on X, formerly Twitter, <a href="https://twitter.com/orcakeiko/status/1523136883370254336" target="_blank" class="icon none">wrote</a> , attaching a picture of a computer part shipped without an Amazon box.</p><p> “Amazon didn&#39;t put my vacuum in an Amazon box — I&#39;m gonna be PISSED if someone steals my package by the time I get home,” another user <a href="https://twitter.com/THEHOLYKOREN/status/1687558410970017793" target="_blank" class="icon none">posted</a> .</p><p> Amazon Help&#39;s X account responded to both, citing its “Frustration-Free Packaging” that reduces the amount of packaging material. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/55ae24ee-8937-4c05-801e-4c3a26301b59.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> The company sees its packaging initiative as a critical evolution after the success of fast-shipping efforts, Lindner said in an interview. Amazon in the past year has doubled down on getting items to customers quickly by overhauling its delivery operations to reduce how far products travel across the US In its new regionalized model, many items stay near one of eight regions, The Wall Street Journal reported <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/amazon-overhauls-delivery-network-to-dispatch-packages-faster-more-cheaply-c10be8b9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">earlier this year.</a></p><p> The massive growth in the company&#39;s warehouse network throughout the pandemic—it roughly doubled its US warehouse space in two years—helps, Lindner said. The less an item has to travel, the easier it is to move without extra packaging. Amazon has cut the distance items travel from fulfillment centers to customers 15%, and decreased “touches,” or how often a package is handled, 12%.</p><p> Amazon tests packages to be eligible to ship without a container, and it says that the system has improved through the use of artificial intelligence. The company performs up to 19 different tests at a facility near its Seattle headquarters that include compressing items, vibrations and drops from different angles.</p><p> One item the company put through its system was a package of screwdrivers. The screwdrivers were originally packaged using soft plastic that made it hazardous to ship without extra protection. Amazon helped the vendor, which it declined to name, design a new, six-sided container that would require no extra packaging.</p><p> Then the company used AI to identify other vendors with similar screwdrivers and shared the new container design with them. The company reduced the size of the package by more than half to about 125 cubic inches, making it less expensive to ship. For 100,000 of the screwdriver packages shipped across a 12-month span, the cost savings through an incentives program tied to the initiative would total about $34,000, Amazon said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/atmospheric/amp.html?guid=C0596D80-1788-478F-AA8C-D31D0091F4BF" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> The Incline Impact Test System at Amazon&#39;s testing facility simulates inclined or horizontal impact during loading of items over 100 pounds. VIDEO: Kholood Eid for The Wall Street Journal<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>“There&#39;s a lot of stuff that we can do on the packaging design for things you never would have expected were even possible,” such as wine glasses, Lindner said. Amazon hasn&#39;t been able to yet figure out how to eliminate extra packaging for some fragile items such as vinyl records.</p><p> Brita, a seller of filtered water pitchers owned by Clorox, changed its packaging to be eligible for Amazon&#39;s program. The company began with its 6- and 10-cup pitchers.</p><p> Brita&#39;s designs for physical stores and e-commerce are different, said Kirstin Ganz, the company&#39;s brand director. To change its packaging for e-commerce, the challenge is to maintain the allure of unboxing without compromising the structure of the box. Brita&#39;s change included making its box open like a gift box to keep that unboxing experience a customer would have otherwise had with tearing open an Amazon box.</p><p> “Finding an e-commerce solution that delivers that sustainability, that safe shipping and that great unboxing experience is complex to achieve,” Ganz said. “It took us some time to get there.”</p><p> Amazon said it made its packaging changes in part because of feedback from customer surveys. The company in recent years has seen a decline in customer satisfaction on product quality and shopping experience, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/amazons-customer-satisfaction-slips-with-shoppers-11668986981?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the Journal reported last year.</a></p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Lindsey Choo contributed to this article. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832946?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> If Amazon successfully delivers more items in just the manufacturer&#39;s packaging, there will be fewer loads with its signature brown boxes like this one that a delivery worker pulls in New York City.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: BRENDAN MCDERMID/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Write to Sebastian Herrera at <a href="mailto:sebastian.herrera@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">sebastian.herrera@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/amazon-deliver-prime-speed-packaging-a616a135</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/amazon-deliver-prime-speed-packaging-a616a135<author><![CDATA[Sebastian Herrera]]></author><category> wsjexchange</category><category>摄影委托</category><category>WSJ公司</category><category>零售批发</category><category>伊泰林</category><category>电子商务</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>零售</category><category>技术</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>Products/Services</category><category> Product/Service Disruptions</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>亚马逊网站</category><category>亚马逊</category><category>Amazon</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>products</category><category> services</category><category> product</category><category> service disruptions</category><category>零售</category><category>批发的</category><category>电子邮寄</category><category>电子商务</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>技术</category></item></channel></rss>